He often expressed his anxiety about this
task, worrying that she would be bored with

2199
02:55:00,610 --> 02:55:02,340
the quiet life they led.

2200
02:55:02,340 --> 02:55:07,550
He wished that there were more young people
in the area, or more types of entertainment.

2201
02:55:07,550 --> 02:55:14,450
He talked about hosting a large dinner party
or even a ball, but it was a dead time of

2202
02:55:14,450 --> 02:55:18,630
year and many of their friends were not at
present in the neighbourhood.

2203
02:55:18,630 --> 02:55:24,541
His worries ended one morning, at last, when
he told Henry that he would bring Eleanor

2204
02:55:24,541 --> 02:55:31,040
and Miss Morland to dinner at his son's house
the next time Henry was at Woodston.

2205
02:55:31,040 --> 02:55:38,340
'And when do you think, sir, I may look forward
to this pleasure?' asked Henry.

2206
02:55:38,340 --> 02:55:44,810
'I am going to Woodston on Monday and will
have business there for at least two or three

2207
02:55:44,810 --> 02:55:45,880
days.'

2208
02:55:45,880 --> 02:55:51,790
'Well, we will take our chances on one of
those days,' General Tilney answered.

2209
02:55:51,790 --> 02:55:54,810
'There is no need to make a firm date.

2210
02:55:54,810 --> 02:55:58,641
We do not expect anything fancy, just whatever
you have in the house will be enough.

2211
02:55:58,641 --> 02:56:07,910
We know that a single man cannot be expected
to produce anything grand.

2212
02:56:07,910 --> 02:56:09,689
What about Wednesday?

2213
02:56:09,689 --> 02:56:14,010
Yes, you may expect us early on Wednesday.'

2214
02:56:14,010 --> 02:56:24,000
A ball itself could not have pleased Catherine
more than a visit to Henry's house in Woodston,

2215
02:56:24,000 --> 02:56:29,580
and her heart was full of joy with the idea
of becoming acquainted with the place.

2216
02:56:29,580 --> 02:56:35,700
Nevertheless she was both surprised and a
little sad when Henry found her and Eleanor

2217
02:56:35,700 --> 02:56:41,250
in the sitting-room an hour later and said,
'I am here, young ladies, to say that our

2218
02:56:41,250 --> 02:56:44,310
pleasures in this world must always be paid
for.

2219
02:56:44,310 --> 02:56:47,960
Look at me at this moment.

2220
02:56:47,960 --> 02:56:53,811
Because I look forward to seeing you both
in my own house on Wednesday, I must leave

2221
02:56:53,811 --> 02:57:00,600
now, two days before I had intended to go,
and I would much rather stay.'

2222
02:57:00,600 --> 02:57:04,880
'But must you go?'

2223
02:57:04,880 --> 02:57:07,420
Catherine asked with a very sad face.

2224
02:57:07,420 --> 02:57:09,430
'Yes, I must!

2225
02:57:09,430 --> 02:57:15,990
My old cook will be frightened half to death
about preparing a dinner for my father.

2226
02:57:15,990 --> 02:57:19,239
She will need as much time as possible to
prepare everything.'

2227
02:57:19,239 --> 02:57:27,229
'But the General told you not to give yourself
any trouble,' said Catherine.

2228
02:57:27,229 --> 02:57:34,330
Henry only smiled, and as he left he said,
'I wish I could reason like you.'

2229
02:57:34,330 --> 02:57:40,439
Catherine always doubted her judgement and
agreed with Henry's, so she had to think about

2230
02:57:40,439 --> 02:57:42,069
this.

2231
02:57:42,069 --> 02:57:46,609
How could people understand each other if
they said one thing so positively and meant

2232
02:57:46,609 --> 02:57:48,170
something else?

2233
02:57:48,170 --> 02:57:55,640
Only Henry and Eleanor could interpret what
their father's words really meant.

2234
02:57:55,640 --> 02:58:02,090
The hours from Saturday to Wednesday passed
very slowly for Catherine.

2235
02:58:02,090 --> 02:58:05,180
Everything was quieter, even rather dull,
without Henry.

2236
02:58:05,180 --> 02:58:10,819
Then she worried that Captain Tilney might
arrive, and she could not imagine acting politely

2237
02:58:10,819 --> 02:58:12,029
towards him.

2238
02:58:12,029 --> 02:58:18,061
She thought a lot about her brother, and felt
sad at having lost Isabella's friendship.

2239
02:58:18,061 --> 02:58:24,271
Her only feeling towards Northanger Abbey
itself was now one of embarrassment, and the

2240
02:58:24,271 --> 02:58:30,430
idea of a country parish with a comfortable
house was much more attractive to her.

2241
02:58:30,430 --> 02:58:36,330
Finally Wednesday arrived and by ten o'clock
the carriage left the Abbey with General Tilney,

2242
02:58:36,330 --> 02:58:42,739
Eleanor and Catherine inside, and after an
agreeable drive of about twenty miles they

2243
02:58:42,739 --> 02:58:47,130
entered Woodston, a large village in pleasant
countryside.

2244
02:58:47,130 --> 02:58:54,029
Catherine looked around and believed that
she preferred it to any place she had ever

2245
02:58:54,029 --> 02:58:55,029
seen.

2246
02:58:55,029 --> 02:59:01,149
They drove through the village, looking at
the neat houses, charming shops and tidy gardens

2247
02:59:01,149 --> 02:59:05,330
until they reached Henry's house at the far
end of the main street.

2248
02:59:05,330 --> 02:59:14,029
It was a newly built, large stone house, and
as they drove up to the door, Henry, with

2249
02:59:14,029 --> 02:59:18,840
three or four energetic dogs, waited at the
door to welcome them.

2250
02:59:18,840 --> 02:59:24,080
When they were inside, the General, who seemed
to think that Catherine would be disappointed

2251
02:59:24,080 --> 02:59:27,540
by the house, began to defend it.

2252
02:59:27,540 --> 02:59:31,720
'We are not calling it a good house.

2253
02:59:31,720 --> 02:59:37,859
It does not compare to Northanger or to Fullerton,
but we feel that it is decent, and not inferior

2254
02:59:37,859 --> 02:59:40,229
to the houses round here.

2255
02:59:40,229 --> 02:59:45,920
I believe that there are very few clergymen
in England with a house half so good.'

2256
02:59:45,920 --> 02:59:52,100
When the party entered the sitting-room, which
was still without furniture, Catherine was

2257
02:59:52,100 --> 02:59:56,730
delighted and her comments satisfied even
the General.

2258
02:59:56,730 --> 03:00:00,180
'What a prettily shaped room!'

2259
03:00:00,180 --> 03:00:01,180
she cried.

2260
03:00:01,180 --> 03:00:02,430
'It is the nicest room I have ever seen.

2261
03:00:02,430 --> 03:00:05,700
And it has a beautiful view.

2262
03:00:05,700 --> 03:00:11,319
You must decorate it soon, Mr Tilney, and
enjoy it.'

2263
03:00:11,319 --> 03:00:17,500
'I believe it needs a lady's touch,' said
the General with a satisfied smile.

2264
03:00:17,500 --> 03:00:25,350
'Well, if it were my house, I would always
sit in this room,' Catherine declared.

2265
03:00:25,350 --> 03:00:31,350
Henry entertained his guests with a wander
round his garden, a look at the stables, and

2266
03:00:31,350 --> 03:00:33,060
then a walk through the village.

2267
03:00:33,060 --> 03:00:39,440
At four they returned to the house for a delicious
meal of many courses, which the General seemed

2268
03:00:39,440 --> 03:00:41,540
extremely pleased by.

2269
03:00:41,540 --> 03:00:47,490
At six o'clock, after General Tilney had had
his coffee, the carriage was waiting at the

2270
03:00:47,490 --> 03:00:51,080
front door for the return trip to Northanger
Abbey.

2271
03:00:51,080 --> 03:00:56,020
Catherine felt certain that she could not
possibly misinterpret the General's behaviour

2272
03:00:56,020 --> 03:00:57,120
that day.

2273
03:00:57,120 --> 03:01:03,899
It seemed clear that he expected her to become
his daughter-in-law; she only wished that

2274
03:01:03,899 --> 03:01:09,149
she could feel as confident about his son's
plans.

2275
03:01:09,149 --> 03:01:16,400
The next morning brought the following unexpected
letter from Isabella:

2276
03:01:16,400 --> 03:01:18,210
Bath, April

2277
03:01:18,210 --> 03:01:20,910
My dearest Catherine,

2278
03:01:20,910 --> 03:01:28,120
I was delighted to receive your two kind letters
and I have a thousand apologies to make for

2279
03:01:28,120 --> 03:01:30,320
not answering them sooner.

2280
03:01:30,320 --> 03:01:36,470
I am quite ashamed at being so idle, but in
this horrible place, one can find time for

2281
03:01:36,470 --> 03:01:37,470
nothing.

2282
03:01:37,470 --> 03:01:42,520
Thank God we leave here tomorrow, so please
direct your next letter to me at my home,

2283
03:01:42,520 --> 03:01:44,490
and write to me soon!

2284
03:01:44,490 --> 03:01:48,399
I have not found any pleasure in Bath since
you left.

2285
03:01:48,399 --> 03:01:53,600
There is so much dust in the air, and everyone
that I care about has left.

2286
03:01:53,600 --> 03:01:58,739
I believe that if I could see you, I could
put up with everything else because you are

2287
03:01:58,739 --> 03:02:01,540
more precious to me than anybody can imagine.

2288
03:02:01,540 --> 03:02:07,399
I am worried about your dear brother, who
I have not heard from since his return to

2289
03:02:07,399 --> 03:02:08,399
Oxford.

2290
03:02:08,399 --> 03:02:14,610
I fear that there has been some misunderstanding
between us, and I am confident that you will

2291
03:02:14,610 --> 03:02:21,989
make my position plain to him: he is the only
man I ever did or ever could love.

2292
03:02:21,989 --> 03:02:26,750
I trust you to make that perfectly clear to
him.

2293
03:02:26,750 --> 03:02:32,420
The spring fashions are in the shops, and
the hats are simply the most awful you can

2294
03:02:32,420 --> 03:02:33,420
imagine.

2295
03:02:33,420 --> 03:02:40,040
I hope you are having a nice time at Northanger
Abbey, but I am afraid you never think of

2296
03:02:40,040 --> 03:02:41,040
me.

2297
03:02:41,040 --> 03:02:46,229
I will not say anything against the family
you are with, although I could if I wanted

2298
03:02:46,229 --> 03:02:48,000
to be spiteful or ungenerous.

2299
03:02:48,000 --> 03:02:54,380
I have learned that young men change their
minds from one day to the next, and I am happy

2300
03:02:54,380 --> 03:03:00,790
to say that the young man whom I dislike more
than all others has left Bath.

2301
03:03:00,790 --> 03:03:06,149
You will guess that I mean Captain Tilney,
who, as you remember, was constantly following

2302
03:03:06,149 --> 03:03:09,529
me and teasing me in the most flirtatious
manner.

2303
03:03:09,529 --> 03:03:13,800
But I know men too well to be fooled by him.

2304
03:03:13,800 --> 03:03:19,189
He returned to his duties in the army two
days ago, and I hope that I will never be

2305
03:03:19,189 --> 03:03:20,810
bothered by him again.

2306
03:03:20,810 --> 03:03:27,020
In the last two days he was in Bath he was
always flirting with Charlotte Davis, a rather

2307
03:03:27,020 --> 03:03:28,200
plain girl.

2308
03:03:28,200 --> 03:03:32,939
I refused to take any notice of him when I
saw him on the street after that.

2309
03:03:32,939 --> 03:03:37,399
What a contrast there is between him and your
brother!

2310
03:03:37,399 --> 03:03:40,850
Please send me news of dear James.

2311
03:03:40,850 --> 03:03:45,950
He seemed so unhappy when he left Bath, perhaps
he had a cold or something else that made

2312
03:03:45,950 --> 03:03:47,030
him feel unwell.

2313
03:03:47,030 --> 03:03:52,970
I would write to him myself but I have lost
his address in Oxford and I worry that he

2314
03:03:52,970 --> 03:03:55,540
misinterpreted my behaviour in some way.

2315
03:03:55,540 --> 03:04:00,000
Ask him to write to me and we will sort everything
out.

2316
03:04:00,000 --> 03:04:06,229
I have not been going out in the evenings,
except that I went to the theatre last night

2317
03:04:06,229 --> 03:04:12,640
with the Hodges, after they teased me about
staying in night after night.

2318
03:04:12,640 --> 03:04:15,600
I had to show them that I was not staying
in because Captain Tilney had gone.

2319
03:04:15,600 --> 03:04:20,620
I went out to show everyone that I have a
good spirit of my own.

2320
03:04:20,620 --> 03:04:23,409
Do you remember Anne Mitchell?

2321
03:04:23,409 --> 03:04:27,860
She was wearing a hat like the one I bought
with you, but it did not suit her.

2322
03:04:27,860 --> 03:04:34,710
I suppose it went with my odd face, at least
Tilney told me so at the time and said every

2323
03:04:34,710 --> 03:04:35,930
eye was looking at me.

2324
03:04:35,930 --> 03:04:40,720
But, of course, he is the last man whose opinion
I would take any notice of.

2325
03:04:40,720 --> 03:04:43,591
I wear purple all the time now.

2326
03:04:43,591 --> 03:04:49,470
I know it is not the best colour for me, but
it is your dear brother's favourite colour.

2327
03:04:49,470 --> 03:04:57,790
Lose no time, my dearest, sweetest Catherine,
in writing to him and to me.

2328
03:04:57,790 --> 03:05:02,580
Your friend forever...

2329
03:05:02,580 --> 03:05:09,620
How could anyone be so false, so dishonest?

2330
03:05:09,620 --> 03:05:15,989
Not even kind-hearted Catherine could be fooled
by so many lies and so much self-interest.

2331
03:05:15,989 --> 03:05:23,140
In fact, Catherine was ashamed of Isabella
and ashamed of ever having loved her.

2332
03:05:23,140 --> 03:05:28,899
Her excuses for her treatment of James were
empty, and Catherine could not believe that

2333
03:05:28,899 --> 03:05:32,910
she had been asked to write to her brother
on Isabella's behalf.

2334
03:05:32,910 --> 03:05:38,620
He had suffered enough and would never hear
Isabella's name mentioned by his sister.

2335
03:05:38,620 --> 03:05:40,609
Never again!

2336
03:05:40,609 --> 03:05:46,270
When Henry returned from Woodston, Catherine
told him and Eleanor about the letter.

2337
03:05:46,270 --> 03:05:51,550
'Your own brother has had a lucky escape,'
Catherine said sincerely.

2338
03:05:51,550 --> 03:05:57,320
'And for me, I wish that I had never met Isabella
Thorpe.

2339
03:05:57,320 --> 03:06:02,410
I can see that she never had any true feelings
for either James or for me.'

2340
03:06:02,410 --> 03:06:07,750
'It will soon seem that you never had met,'
Henry said.

2341
03:06:07,750 --> 03:06:12,580
'But please explain one more thing for me,'
Catherine replied.

2342
03:06:12,580 --> 03:06:17,230
'She was obviously pursuing your brother but
did not succeed.

2343
03:06:17,230 --> 03:06:21,100
But I do not understand Captain Tilney's behaviour
in this affair.

2344
03:06:21,100 --> 03:06:28,479
Why did he flirt with her and make her quarrel
with my brother, and then walk away from her?'

2345
03:06:28,479 --> 03:06:35,760
'I cannot explain my brother's motives, but
like Miss Thorpe, he thinks very highly of

2346
03:06:35,760 --> 03:06:36,760
himself.

2347
03:06:36,760 --> 03:06:42,890
Until this time, he has not been hurt by his
flirtations,' explained Henry.

2348
03:06:42,890 --> 03:06:47,319
'I believe that he never really cared for
your friend.'

2349
03:06:47,319 --> 03:06:53,689
'Well, I disapprove of this sort of behaviour,'
Catherine said quite angrily, 'and I must

2350
03:06:53,689 --> 03:06:56,431
say that I do not like Captain Tilney at all.

2351
03:06:56,431 --> 03:07:04,240
I suppose that no great harm has been done
to me or to my brother, but what would have

2352
03:07:04,240 --> 03:07:08,820
happened if Isabella had lost her heart to
him?'

2353
03:07:08,820 --> 03:07:14,380
'But we must first assume that Isabella had
a heart to lose, which would make her a different

2354
03:07:14,380 --> 03:07:19,950
young woman, and so she would have received
very different treatment from my brother,'

2355
03:07:19,950 --> 03:07:21,340
replied Henry.

2356
03:07:21,340 --> 03:07:26,260
'It is good that you defend your brother,'
said Catherine.

2357
03:07:26,260 --> 03:07:31,760
'And you must defend your brother's position
and understand that he should not feel sad

2358
03:07:31,760 --> 03:07:33,330
about losing Miss Thorpe.

2359
03:07:33,330 --> 03:07:36,149
He has had a lucky escape.

2360
03:07:36,149 --> 03:07:40,540
Your own sense of what is right and wrong
is so strong that you have not even thought

2361
03:07:40,540 --> 03:07:42,840
of revenge against your friend.

2362
03:07:42,840 --> 03:07:46,989
I admire you very much for that.'

2363
03:07:46,989 --> 03:07:51,180
Henry's admiration was enough to make Catherine
feel better in any situation.

2364
03:07:51,180 --> 03:07:57,710
She was determined not to think that Captain
Tilney was completely evil; she decided she

2365
03:07:57,710 --> 03:08:01,819
would never answer Isabella's letter, and
she tried not to think about what had happened

2366
03:08:01,819 --> 03:08:06,250
in Bath between those two ever again.

2367
03:08:06,250 --> 03:08:09,580
CHAPTER TEN

2368
03:08:09,580 --> 03:08:16,340
A Perfect Visit Ends in Disaster

2369
03:08:16,340 --> 03:08:21,200
A few days later, the General announced that
he had to go to London on business for a week.

2370
03:08:21,200 --> 03:08:27,000
As he was leaving, he said, 'Miss Morland,
more than anything, I regret that I will be

2371
03:08:27,000 --> 03:08:30,100
robbed of your charming company for a whole
week.

2372
03:08:30,100 --> 03:08:34,970
I have instructed Eleanor and Henry to look
after you, and I hope you will tell them if

2373
03:08:34,970 --> 03:08:40,521
there is anything they can do to make your
stay more amusing or more comfortable.'

2374
03:08:40,521 --> 03:08:48,240
The General's departure gave Catherine her
first understanding of the principle that

2375
03:08:48,240 --> 03:08:51,779
a loss may sometimes be a gain.

2376
03:08:51,779 --> 03:08:58,029
The three young people had much more fun without
General Tilney in control of their lives.

2377
03:08:58,029 --> 03:09:04,750
Every meal was a scene of enjoyment and ease,
and every day was spent as the three wished.

2378
03:09:04,750 --> 03:09:11,310
These delightful days made our heroine love
the place and the people more and more.

2379
03:09:11,310 --> 03:09:17,820
Catherine was now in the fourth week of her
visit and had never been happier.

2380
03:09:17,820 --> 03:09:23,360
But the fact that she had been there for almost
a month made her wonder whether it was polite

2381
03:09:23,360 --> 03:09:29,490
to stay any longer, or whether she should
suggest choosing a date for her return to

2382
03:09:29,490 --> 03:09:30,490
Fullerton.

2383
03:09:30,490 --> 03:09:35,870
Although it was an unpleasant subject, Catherine
took the first opportunity to speak to Eleanor

2384
03:09:35,870 --> 03:09:37,130
about it.

2385
03:09:37,130 --> 03:09:44,390
'Dear Eleanor, I think I must return home
soon.'

2386
03:09:44,390 --> 03:09:51,330
'Oh, Catherine,' Eleanor began with feeling,
'I had hoped for the pleasure of your company

2387
03:09:51,330 --> 03:09:53,601
for a much longer time.

2388
03:09:53,601 --> 03:10:00,060
If your parents knew how much we enjoyed having
you here, do you think they might allow you

2389
03:10:00,060 --> 03:10:03,520
to stay a bit longer?'

2390
03:10:03,520 --> 03:10:08,830
'Oh, my parents are in no hurry to have me
at home.

2391
03:10:08,830 --> 03:10:12,180
They are always satisfied if I am happy.'

2392
03:10:12,180 --> 03:10:19,160
'Then why are you in such a hurry to leave
us?' asked Eleanor with a worried look on

2393
03:10:19,160 --> 03:10:20,160
her face.

2394
03:10:20,160 --> 03:10:23,690
'But I have been here so long!'

2395
03:10:23,690 --> 03:10:24,800
Catherine cried.

2396
03:10:24,800 --> 03:10:32,960
'If you have grown tired of being here, I
cannot urge you to stay,' Eleanor said sadly.

2397
03:10:32,960 --> 03:10:35,920
'Oh, no, you misunderstand me!

2398
03:10:35,920 --> 03:10:45,250
For my own pleasure, I would be very happy
to stay another four weeks, but I do not wish

2399
03:10:45,250 --> 03:10:46,470
to become a nuisance.'

2400
03:10:46,470 --> 03:10:48,189
'Catherine, it is settled then.

2401
03:10:48,189 --> 03:10:50,189
You must not think of leaving us.

2402
03:10:50,189 --> 03:10:55,440
Henry and I will be very sad to lose you,
so you must stay as long as possible.'

2403
03:10:55,440 --> 03:11:03,400
Eleanor's desire for her to stay longer at
Northanger Abbey was so sincere that it confirmed

2404
03:11:03,400 --> 03:11:09,870
Catherine's secret belief that the Tilneys
hoped she would belong to their family one

2405
03:11:09,870 --> 03:11:11,260
day.

2406
03:11:11,260 --> 03:11:18,330
Henry's obligations at Woodston took him away
during his father's absence, but Catherine

2407
03:11:18,330 --> 03:11:22,810
continued to be happy because it gave her
time to get to know Eleanor better and to

2408
03:11:22,810 --> 03:11:24,950
enjoy her company.

2409
03:11:24,950 --> 03:11:29,380
On the evening of Henry's departure, the young
ladies were still sitting and chatting at

2410
03:11:29,380 --> 03:11:35,729
the dinner table at eleven o'clock, a rather
late hour at the Abbey.

2411
03:11:35,729 --> 03:11:39,580
Then as they walked to their bedrooms, they
heard a carriage arrive outside, and in the

2412
03:11:39,580 --> 03:11:43,240
next moment they heard the loud noise of the
doorbell.

2413
03:11:43,240 --> 03:11:46,630
'Who could that be at this late hour?'

2414
03:11:46,630 --> 03:11:47,830
wondered Eleanor.

2415
03:11:47,830 --> 03:11:49,250
'It must be Frederick.

2416
03:11:49,250 --> 03:11:54,920
I will say good night, dear Catherine, and
go downstairs to welcome him.'

2417
03:11:54,920 --> 03:11:59,880
Catherine went into her room, thinking about
meeting Captain Tilney the next morning at

2418
03:11:59,880 --> 03:12:01,320
breakfast.

2419
03:12:01,320 --> 03:12:07,870
She hoped that he would not mention Isabella's
name, or the part he had played in her brother's

2420
03:12:07,870 --> 03:12:08,930
unhappiness.

2421
03:12:08,930 --> 03:12:14,140
She thought she could be polite to him as
long as no one talked about Bath.

2422
03:12:14,140 --> 03:12:21,580
Half an hour later, Catherine heard someone
come up the stairs and then her door opened

2423
03:12:21,580 --> 03:12:23,080
very gently.

2424
03:12:23,080 --> 03:12:27,580
Eleanor came into her room, looking pale and
quite nervous.

2425
03:12:27,580 --> 03:12:32,881
Catherine worried that Captain Tilney was
in some kind of trouble and made Eleanor sit

2426
03:12:32,881 --> 03:12:35,160
down.

2427
03:12:35,160 --> 03:12:43,890
After a minute or two of silence, Miss Tilney
said, 'My dear Catherine, I have come to you

2428
03:12:43,890 --> 03:12:47,130
with bad news.

2429
03:12:47,130 --> 03:12:49,880
And I do not know how to tell you about it.

2430
03:12:49,880 --> 03:12:52,700
Oh, how shall I tell you?'

2431
03:12:52,700 --> 03:12:55,170
'Has something happened to Henry?

2432
03:12:55,170 --> 03:13:00,970
Is there a messenger from Woodston downstairs?'

2433
03:13:00,970 --> 03:13:04,690
'No, it is not anyone from Woodston.

2434
03:13:04,690 --> 03:13:07,110
My father himself has arrived.'

2435
03:13:07,110 --> 03:13:13,810
Eleanor's voice shook and she looked at the
carpet when she said, 'my father'.

2436
03:13:13,810 --> 03:13:19,010
Catherine was disappointed to know that General
Tilney had returned early, but she waited

2437
03:13:19,010 --> 03:13:21,220
for Eleanor to explain more.

2438
03:13:21,220 --> 03:13:32,950
'You are so good and kind, a friend who will
understand how difficult this is for me, especially

2439
03:13:32,950 --> 03:13:37,800
after we had happily agreed that you would
stay for another four weeks.

2440
03:13:37,800 --> 03:13:42,890
I am an unwilling messenger who has to tell
you that we must part.

2441
03:13:42,890 --> 03:13:49,109
My father has remembered that we accepted
an invitation to go to Lord Longtown's house,

2442
03:13:49,109 --> 03:13:51,710
near Hereford, for a fortnight.

2443
03:13:51,710 --> 03:13:54,069
We leave on Monday.

2444
03:13:54,069 --> 03:13:58,600
Explanation and apology are equally impossible.

2445
03:13:58,600 --> 03:14:01,160
My heart is too heavy to attempt either.'

2446
03:14:01,160 --> 03:14:05,229
'My dear Eleanor, don't be distressed.

2447
03:14:05,229 --> 03:14:12,470
I am very, very sorry that we must part so
soon, but I am not offended.

2448
03:14:12,470 --> 03:14:19,101
An earlier engagement must take priority,
and I can finish my visit later, or you can

2449
03:14:19,101 --> 03:14:21,739
come to me at Fullerton after Hereford.'

2450
03:14:21,739 --> 03:14:27,700
'It will not be in my power to do that,' Eleanor
said quietly.

2451
03:14:27,700 --> 03:14:31,340
'Come to Fullerton when you can, then.'

2452
03:14:31,340 --> 03:14:39,130
Eleanor did not respond to this suggestion,
and Catherine continued, 'Monday is very soon.

2453
03:14:39,130 --> 03:14:41,529
And are you all going?

2454
03:14:41,529 --> 03:14:46,300
Don't worry, Eleanor, I can be ready to go
on Monday morning.

2455
03:14:46,300 --> 03:14:48,840
We can be together until it is time for you
to depart.

2456
03:14:48,840 --> 03:14:54,410
It will not bother my parents if I show up
unannounced on Monday evening.

2457
03:14:54,410 --> 03:14:59,370
The General will send a servant with me, I
imagine, for half the trip, and then I will

2458
03:14:59,370 --> 03:15:04,060
be at Salisbury and only nine miles from home.'

2459
03:15:04,060 --> 03:15:09,700
'Catherine, I wish I could tell you that those
were the arrangements.

2460
03:15:09,700 --> 03:15:12,601
But - what can I say?

2461
03:15:12,601 --> 03:15:19,410
You must leave us tomorrow morning; the carriage
has been ordered to be waiting for you at

2462
03:15:19,410 --> 03:15:28,319
seven o'clock and no servant will accompany
you.'

2463
03:15:28,319 --> 03:15:33,560
Catherine sank into a chair, unable to breathe
or to speak.

2464
03:15:33,560 --> 03:15:42,570
'Dear Catherine,' Eleanor continued, 'I could
hardly believe my senses when I was told.

2465
03:15:42,570 --> 03:15:46,700
No disappointment or anger on your part could
be greater than my own.

2466
03:15:46,700 --> 03:15:52,390
What will your father and mother say after
we took you away from the Allens, your true

2467
03:15:52,390 --> 03:15:56,609
friends, and brought you here, so far from
your home?

2468
03:15:56,609 --> 03:16:02,080
And now you are cruelly driven out of the
house without the smallest consideration for

2469
03:16:02,080 --> 03:16:03,680
your comfort or safety.

2470
03:16:03,680 --> 03:16:10,910
Dear, dear Catherine, I had to deliver the
message, but you know that I have no real

2471
03:16:10,910 --> 03:16:12,600
power in this house.

2472
03:16:12,600 --> 03:16:17,050
I think you know who is responsible for this
insult.'

2473
03:16:17,050 --> 03:16:21,960
'Have I offended the General?'

2474
03:16:21,960 --> 03:16:23,439
Catherine asked weakly.

2475
03:16:23,439 --> 03:16:30,970
'I can think of nothing that you have done
to offend him, but I have never seen him so

2476
03:16:30,970 --> 03:16:31,970
angry.'

2477
03:16:31,970 --> 03:16:36,750
Catherine struggled to speak for Eleanor's
sake.

2478
03:16:36,750 --> 03:16:45,400
'I am very sorry if I have upset him; it is
the last thing I would do on purpose.

2479
03:16:45,400 --> 03:16:48,050
But don't be unhappy, Eleanor.

2480
03:16:48,050 --> 03:16:52,390
You must go to Hereford and keep your engagement.

2481
03:16:52,390 --> 03:16:58,399
I am only sorry that the trip was not remembered
sooner so I could have written home.

2482
03:16:58,399 --> 03:17:00,890
But it will not matter to my family.

2483
03:17:00,890 --> 03:17:03,069
They will be happy to see me.'

2484
03:17:03,069 --> 03:17:06,400
'But you should not have to make the journey
alone!'

2485
03:17:06,400 --> 03:17:08,360
'The journey is nothing.

2486
03:17:08,360 --> 03:17:11,300
It is less than seventy miles.

2487
03:17:11,300 --> 03:17:13,250
Don't think about that.

2488
03:17:13,250 --> 03:17:16,189
I can be ready at seven.

2489
03:17:16,189 --> 03:17:19,819
Please ask your servant to call me in time.'

2490
03:17:19,819 --> 03:17:27,810
After Eleanor left, Catherine burst into tears.

2491
03:17:27,810 --> 03:17:30,170
She was being thrown out!

2492
03:17:30,170 --> 03:17:35,569
With no reasonable explanation nor apology
from General Tilney, she was being rudely

2493
03:17:35,569 --> 03:17:36,620
sent home.

2494
03:17:36,620 --> 03:17:43,239
She could not even say goodbye to Henry, and
what about her hopes?

2495
03:17:43,239 --> 03:17:47,069
Would she ever see him again?

2496
03:17:47,069 --> 03:17:54,949
How could a man who had been so polite and
kind to her, who had treated her fondly throughout

2497
03:17:54,949 --> 03:18:02,189
her time at Northanger Abbey, now act so rudely
towards her?

2498
03:18:02,189 --> 03:18:08,760
She must have offended him in some way and
given him reasons for treating her so badly.

2499
03:18:08,760 --> 03:18:10,810
Seven o'clock!

2500
03:18:10,810 --> 03:18:19,640
He wanted her out of the house before he left
his bedroom in the morning.

2501
03:18:19,640 --> 03:18:28,280
Catherine spent another sleepless night at
Northanger Abbey, but this time she was not

2502
03:18:28,280 --> 03:18:32,510
frightened by imagined ghosts and mysterious
chests and cupboards.

2503
03:18:32,510 --> 03:18:41,010
This time her anxiety had a basis in fact,
and neither the wind nor the darkness bothered

2504
03:18:41,010 --> 03:18:42,010
her.

2505
03:18:42,010 --> 03:18:47,320
Instead, she lay awake wondering how things
had gone so badly wrong.

2506
03:18:47,320 --> 03:18:52,430
By the time Eleanor came to her room at six
in the morning Catherine had finished her

2507
03:18:52,430 --> 03:18:55,840
packing, and she was almost dressed and ready
to depart.

2508
03:18:55,840 --> 03:19:01,390
Both young women remained silent, neither
knowing how to improve the situation.

2509
03:19:01,390 --> 03:19:06,710
At the breakfast table, Catherine could not
eat, but she thought about breakfast the day

2510
03:19:06,710 --> 03:19:07,710
before.

2511
03:19:07,710 --> 03:19:10,140
Happy, happy breakfast!

2512
03:19:10,140 --> 03:19:17,080
Henry had been there and the three of them
had chatted, enjoying everything present,

2513
03:19:17,080 --> 03:19:23,229
and fearing nothing in the future except Henry's
visit to Woodston for a few days.

2514
03:19:23,229 --> 03:19:28,689
Henry had sat beside her and helped her to
food, and so Catherine now lost herself in

2515
03:19:28,689 --> 03:19:30,060
this memory.

2516
03:19:30,060 --> 03:19:34,930
Then she heard the carriage arrive outside
and remembered what was happening.

2517
03:19:34,930 --> 03:19:41,400
Eleanor now felt the need to speak and hurried
to say, 'You must write to me, Catherine,

2518
03:19:41,400 --> 03:19:42,770
as soon as possible.

2519
03:19:42,770 --> 03:19:47,560
You must tell me you are safe at home and
have found your family well.

2520
03:19:47,560 --> 03:19:49,500
I will not expect more.

2521
03:19:49,500 --> 03:19:54,750
Please send a letter to me at Lord Longtown's,
but address it to his daughter, my friend

2522
03:19:54,750 --> 03:19:55,790
Alice.'

2523
03:19:55,790 --> 03:20:03,979
'No, Eleanor,' Catherine answered quietly,
'if you are not allowed to receive a letter

2524
03:20:03,979 --> 03:20:07,921
from me, I think I had better not write.

2525
03:20:07,921 --> 03:20:10,430
I will have no trouble getting home safely.'

2526
03:20:10,430 --> 03:20:16,779
'I am not surprised by your feelings, dear
Catherine, and will not urge you to do something

2527
03:20:16,779 --> 03:20:22,420
you are unhappy about,' Eleanor answered sadly,
with tears in her eyes.

2528
03:20:22,420 --> 03:20:26,730
'Oh, Eleanor, I will write to you.

2529
03:20:26,730 --> 03:20:28,100
Please don't worry.'

2530
03:20:28,100 --> 03:20:32,010
'Thank you, Catherine, and there is one more
thing.

2531
03:20:32,010 --> 03:20:37,149
You have been so long away from home that
I wonder if you have any money left for the

2532
03:20:37,149 --> 03:20:38,149
journey.'

2533
03:20:38,149 --> 03:20:43,490
Catherine quickly looked into her purse and
said, 'I had not thought about money, but

2534
03:20:43,490 --> 03:20:44,490
you are right.

2535
03:20:44,490 --> 03:20:48,120
I cannot pay for the journey to Fullerton.'

2536
03:20:48,120 --> 03:20:52,630
Eleanor gave Catherine money from her own
purse.

2537
03:20:52,630 --> 03:20:57,810
Soon the carriage was announced to be ready;
and Catherine and Eleanor's silent, sad looks

2538
03:20:57,810 --> 03:21:00,840
expressed more than any words could.

2539
03:21:00,840 --> 03:21:05,580
They hurried to the door, and Catherine was
soon climbing into the carriage.

2540
03:21:05,580 --> 03:21:11,710
But she could not leave until she had asked
Eleanor with trembling lips to give her kind

2541
03:21:11,710 --> 03:21:14,729
regards to her absent friend.

2542
03:21:14,729 --> 03:21:24,160
But by almost mentioning his name, Catherine's
tears began again and she found her seat and

2543
03:21:24,160 --> 03:21:27,720
covered her face with her handkerchief.

2544
03:21:27,720 --> 03:21:31,160
CHAPTER ELEVEN

2545
03:21:31,160 --> 03:21:37,069
Reliable Family Life

2546
03:21:37,069 --> 03:21:41,960
Catherine felt too unhappy to be frightened
by the journey to Fullerton, and began it

2547
03:21:41,960 --> 03:21:45,340
without worrying about its length or about
being alone.

2548
03:21:45,340 --> 03:21:52,399
Leaning back in the corner of the carriage,
crying and feeling cruelly treated, she had

2549
03:21:52,399 --> 03:21:57,029
gone a number of miles beyond the walls of
Northanger Abbey before she raised her head

2550
03:21:57,029 --> 03:21:59,560
and looked out of the window.

2551
03:21:59,560 --> 03:22:04,670
She recognised the road as the same one that
had taken her to Woodston only ten days earlier,

2552
03:22:04,670 --> 03:22:08,601
and she suffered even more as she thought
about the difference between that trip and

2553
03:22:08,601 --> 03:22:09,660
this one.

2554
03:22:09,660 --> 03:22:15,010
Every mile, as it brought her nearer Woodston,
added to her grief.

2555
03:22:15,010 --> 03:22:19,979
When the carriage passed the road that led
directly to Woodston, Catherine thought of

2556
03:22:19,979 --> 03:22:23,650
Henry and the day that she had spent at his
house there.

2557
03:22:23,650 --> 03:22:26,790
It had been one of the happiest days of her
life.

2558
03:22:26,790 --> 03:22:31,899
On that occasion the General had given her
the impression that he actually wished for

2559
03:22:31,899 --> 03:22:33,430
Henry to marry her.

2560
03:22:33,430 --> 03:22:41,649
Yes, only ten days ago she had felt so happy
about the future, and now, what had she done

2561
03:22:41,649 --> 03:22:46,670
or not done to deserve such a change in the
General's opinion of her?

2562
03:22:46,670 --> 03:22:52,480
The only offence against General Tilney that
Catherine could accuse herself of was her

2563
03:22:52,480 --> 03:22:56,050
shocking suspicions about what had happened
to his wife.

2564
03:22:56,050 --> 03:23:00,880
But Catherine trusted that her secret was
safe with Henry; he would not have betrayed

2565
03:23:00,880 --> 03:23:01,880
her.

2566
03:23:01,880 --> 03:23:06,090
It was impossible for the General to know
that she once wondered if he might have murdered

2567
03:23:06,090 --> 03:23:10,239
his wife or made her a prisoner in her own
home.

2568
03:23:10,239 --> 03:23:16,110
Of course if he did know about her suspicions,
he would have a good reason to ask her to

2569
03:23:16,110 --> 03:23:22,699
leave, but she believed in Henry and was certain
that her secret was safe with him.

2570
03:23:22,699 --> 03:23:27,340
But more than anything, Catherine was anxious
about Henry's feelings when he returned to

2571
03:23:27,340 --> 03:23:30,290
the Abbey and found that she had been sent
away.

2572
03:23:30,290 --> 03:23:33,880
Would he accept his father's reasons for throwing
her out?

2573
03:23:33,880 --> 03:23:39,120
Or would he regret that she was gone and hate
his father for sending her home?

2574
03:23:39,120 --> 03:23:46,351
Would he argue with his father or remain obedient
and talk only to Eleanor about his true feelings?

2575
03:23:46,351 --> 03:23:52,561
While thinking over many questions and struggling
with doubts about herself, Catherine hardly

2576
03:23:52,561 --> 03:23:55,500
noticed the hours and miles flying by.

2577
03:23:55,500 --> 03:24:02,120
How would she explain to her family the circumstances
surrounding her sudden return to Fullerton?

2578
03:24:02,120 --> 03:24:08,490
Would there be any pleasure in returning home
with such a story to tell?

2579
03:24:08,490 --> 03:24:14,040
How could she make it clear to them that Henry
and Eleanor were the finest, most interesting

2580
03:24:14,040 --> 03:24:17,190
and most reliable friends she had ever known?

2581
03:24:17,190 --> 03:24:22,210
How could she separate them from General Tilney
in her family's opinion?

2582
03:24:22,210 --> 03:24:26,980
It would break her heart if her family judged
her friends unfairly.

2583
03:24:26,980 --> 03:24:33,260
Finally, after a journey which had taken more
than eleven hours without accident or alarm,

2584
03:24:33,260 --> 03:24:37,830
Catherine reached Fullerton just after six
thirty in the evening.

2585
03:24:37,830 --> 03:24:43,040
We would expect a heroine to return to her
native village after achieving great things,

2586
03:24:43,040 --> 03:24:46,350
with many stories of success to be proud of.

2587
03:24:46,350 --> 03:24:52,880
But this homecoming was very different from
what you or she might have hoped for.

2588
03:24:52,880 --> 03:24:59,860
Our heroine was returning home disappointed,
alone and without hope or joy.

2589
03:24:59,860 --> 03:25:05,340
Therefore, her carriage passed quickly through
the village and Catherine hurried into her

2590
03:25:05,340 --> 03:25:08,979
house, unwilling to meet the questioning eyes
of friends and neighbours.

2591
03:25:08,979 --> 03:25:16,300
But you must remember that the Morland family
would not have high expectations of any great

2592
03:25:16,300 --> 03:25:18,780
achievements or successes for Catherine.

2593
03:25:18,780 --> 03:25:24,070
Instead, although they would be surprised
by her unexpected arrival, they would simply

2594
03:25:24,070 --> 03:25:27,030
be very happy to have her at home again.

2595
03:25:27,030 --> 03:25:33,279
The two youngest children, a boy and girl
of six and four years old, looked out when

2596
03:25:33,279 --> 03:25:38,359
they heard the carriage stop at their gate,
expecting, as usual, to see a brother or sister

2597
03:25:38,359 --> 03:25:39,890
arrive home.

2598
03:25:39,890 --> 03:25:46,120
But when they saw that it was Catherine returning
after an absence of eleven weeks, they jumped

2599
03:25:46,120 --> 03:25:52,529
for joy, shouted for their parents and ran
out to greet their older sister.

2600
03:25:52,529 --> 03:25:56,660
The warm, affectionate welcome that Catherine
received from her parents and brothers and

2601
03:25:56,660 --> 03:26:02,989
sisters awakened the best feelings in her
heart, and she found her troubled spirit calmed;

2602
03:26:02,989 --> 03:26:06,960
she even, at first, felt happy!

2603
03:26:06,960 --> 03:26:12,470
But Mrs Morland noticed that the poor traveller
looked pale and tired, and soon had the family

2604
03:26:12,470 --> 03:26:13,689
seated round the tea-table.

2605
03:26:13,689 --> 03:26:19,819
With cups of tea and sandwiches in front of
them, everyone was eager to hear about Catherine's

2606
03:26:19,819 --> 03:26:25,630
adventures and to find out why she had come
home without warning.

2607
03:26:25,630 --> 03:26:31,979
Quite slowly, and with much hesitation, Catherine
tried to explain what had happened the night

2608
03:26:31,979 --> 03:26:38,840
before, and although her parents were usually
unwilling to criticise other people, they

2609
03:26:38,840 --> 03:26:42,590
felt unable to pardon this insult to their
daughter.

2610
03:26:42,590 --> 03:26:48,930
They believed that General Tilney had acted
neither honourably nor kindly as a gentleman

2611
03:26:48,930 --> 03:26:51,620
or as a parent.

2612
03:26:51,620 --> 03:26:54,739
What could have made him treat a guest so
badly?

2613
03:26:54,739 --> 03:27:01,410
Like Catherine, they could see no reason for
his rude behaviour, especially after he had

2614
03:27:01,410 --> 03:27:05,500
treated her so well for the past four weeks.

2615
03:27:05,500 --> 03:27:15,649
Finally, Mrs Morland ended the conversation
by saying, 'It is a strange business and General

2616
03:27:15,649 --> 03:27:22,300
Tilney must be a strange man, but you are
home now, safe and secure.

2617
03:27:22,300 --> 03:27:28,439
It is not worth troubling yourself any further
about that man's reasons.'

2618
03:27:28,439 --> 03:27:36,750
'But why couldn't he send Catherine home in
the proper manner if he had to leave for Hereford?'

2619
03:27:36,750 --> 03:27:39,920
asked Sarah, the eldest of Catherine's sisters.

2620
03:27:39,920 --> 03:27:44,860
'I do not think we will discover his reasons,'
answered Mrs Morland.

2621
03:27:44,860 --> 03:27:50,620
'I feel sorry for his own children, who must
have a difficult time with him as their father.

2622
03:27:50,620 --> 03:27:57,520
But you managed well on your long trip, Catherine,
and I am very proud of you.

2623
03:27:57,520 --> 03:28:01,979
I believe you have grown up quite a lot in
the last eleven weeks.

2624
03:28:01,979 --> 03:28:09,010
I am glad I did not know of your journey while
it was happening, but now it has ended perhaps

2625
03:28:09,010 --> 03:28:12,199
there is no great harm done.

2626
03:28:12,199 --> 03:28:16,090
You are not the same little girl that we said
goodbye to eleven weeks ago.

2627
03:28:16,090 --> 03:28:23,640
You have grown up and can take care of yourself
now.'

2628
03:28:23,640 --> 03:28:27,649
Catherine hoped that her mother was right
about that, but her spirits were quite worn

2629
03:28:27,649 --> 03:28:31,750
down and she longed to be silent and alone.

2630
03:28:31,750 --> 03:28:36,150
She was happy to agree to her mother's suggestion
that she should go to bed early and gain the

2631
03:28:36,150 --> 03:28:38,380
benefit of a good night's rest.

2632
03:28:38,380 --> 03:28:44,811
Her parents knew she was tired and disappointed,
but they had not guessed that she was also

2633
03:28:44,811 --> 03:28:46,609
suffering from a broken heart.

2634
03:28:46,609 --> 03:28:51,890
Perhaps it is odd that with a young daughter
of seventeen just returning from her first

2635
03:28:51,890 --> 03:28:58,939
adventure away from home, they had not thought
of that.

2636
03:28:58,939 --> 03:29:05,609
As soon as breakfast had ended the next morning,
Catherine sat down to write the promised letter

2637
03:29:05,609 --> 03:29:08,479
to her friend at Northanger Abbey.

2638
03:29:08,479 --> 03:29:12,640
She regretted the cold manner in which she
had left Eleanor Tilney, and the fact that

2639
03:29:12,640 --> 03:29:15,700
she had never valued her kindness and character
enough.

2640
03:29:15,700 --> 03:29:20,460
But most of all, she worried about leaving
Eleanor to deal with General Tilney and his

2641
03:29:20,460 --> 03:29:22,740
difficult nature.

2642
03:29:22,740 --> 03:29:27,930
She wanted her letter to say how grateful
she was without reminding Eleanor of how the

2643
03:29:27,930 --> 03:29:29,199
visit had ended.

2644
03:29:29,199 --> 03:29:35,760
She wanted to be careful without being cold,
honest without placing blame.

2645
03:29:35,760 --> 03:29:42,080
She did not want to cause Eleanor any pain,
and she did not want to embarrass herself

2646
03:29:42,080 --> 03:29:44,260
in case Henry saw the letter.

2647
03:29:44,260 --> 03:29:50,939
In the end, Catherine wrote a very short note
in which she expressed her grateful thanks

2648
03:29:50,939 --> 03:29:55,610
and her affectionate good wishes for Eleanor
and her brother, and in which she returned

2649
03:29:55,610 --> 03:29:58,399
the money Eleanor had given her for her journey.

2650
03:29:58,399 --> 03:30:06,410
'This is a very strange friendship,' said
Mrs Morland when Catherine had finished her

2651
03:30:06,410 --> 03:30:07,410
letter.

2652
03:30:07,410 --> 03:30:11,010
'Soon made and soon ended.

2653
03:30:11,010 --> 03:30:18,150
I am sorry that you were disappointed, because
Mrs Allen had only good things to say about

2654
03:30:18,150 --> 03:30:19,210
the Tilney children.

2655
03:30:19,210 --> 03:30:23,680
And you were so unlucky with your friend Isabella
too.

2656
03:30:23,680 --> 03:30:27,430
And poor James!

2657
03:30:27,430 --> 03:30:36,811
Well, we must live and learn; I hope your
next new friends will be more worth keeping.'

2658
03:30:36,811 --> 03:30:43,670
Catherine's cheeks went red as she warmly
answered, 'No friend can be more worth keeping

2659
03:30:43,670 --> 03:30:45,220
than Eleanor.'

2660
03:30:45,220 --> 03:30:50,851
'If that is true, Catherine, I hope that you
and she will meet again some time in the next

2661
03:30:50,851 --> 03:30:51,851
few years.

2662
03:30:51,851 --> 03:30:58,939
It is very likely to happen - imagine what
a pleasure it will be to see her again.'

2663
03:30:58,939 --> 03:31:04,310
But Catherine was not thinking only of Eleanor
as she listened to her mother's kind, but

2664
03:31:04,310 --> 03:31:05,310
painful words.

2665
03:31:05,310 --> 03:31:10,399
What would happen to Henry Tilney if she did
not meet him for a few years?

2666
03:31:10,399 --> 03:31:14,190
Her eyes filled with tears as she imagined
such a meeting.

2667
03:31:14,190 --> 03:31:19,140
He might have forgotten her and have met another
young woman who attracted him.

2668
03:31:19,140 --> 03:31:25,951
The next time she saw him, he might be a married
man with a family of his own - he might not

2669
03:31:25,951 --> 03:31:29,310
even recognise her!

2670
03:31:29,310 --> 03:31:34,330
Mrs Morland was disturbed by her daughter's
tears and proposed a visit to Mrs Allen.

2671
03:31:34,330 --> 03:31:38,670
And so mother and daughter began the walk
to their neighbour's house, which was less

2672
03:31:38,670 --> 03:31:40,930
than a quarter of a mile distant.

2673
03:31:40,930 --> 03:31:46,960
As they walked, Mrs Morland gave Catherine
her opinion of James's broken engagement.

2674
03:31:46,960 --> 03:31:55,771
'Of course we are sorry for James, but it
is good that the engagement has ended, and

2675
03:31:55,771 --> 03:31:57,740
there is no harm done in the end.

2676
03:31:57,740 --> 03:32:02,810
We did not know Miss Thorpe, and she had no
personal fortune.

2677
03:32:02,810 --> 03:32:08,279
And now, after such improper behaviour, we
have a very poor opinion of her.

2678
03:32:08,279 --> 03:32:14,149
James will recover, and I am sure that he
will use better judgement next time.'

2679
03:32:14,149 --> 03:32:21,109
Her mother's thoughts made Catherine reflect
on the changes in her own circumstances.

2680
03:32:21,109 --> 03:32:27,311
Three months ago she had been full of happy
expectations and had run between her home

2681
03:32:27,311 --> 03:32:33,960
and the Allens' house ten times a day with
a light heart and an independent spirit, looking

2682
03:32:33,960 --> 03:32:37,410
forward to new pleasures and without a care
in the world.

2683
03:32:37,410 --> 03:32:45,160
She could picture herself three months ago,
and now what a different young woman she was!

2684
03:32:45,160 --> 03:32:51,960
The Allens were surprised, but very glad,
to see Catherine, and they too were very angry

2685
03:32:51,960 --> 03:32:56,610
and displeased on learning how she had been
treated by General Tilney.

2686
03:32:56,610 --> 03:33:01,960
'Catherine surprised us yesterday evening,'
reported Mrs Morland.

2687
03:33:01,960 --> 03:33:07,300
'She travelled all the way in a carriage by
herself and knew nothing about her journey

2688
03:33:07,300 --> 03:33:09,290
until late Saturday night.

2689
03:33:09,290 --> 03:33:13,770
General Tilney returned home with the strange
idea that he was tired of having her in his

2690
03:33:13,770 --> 03:33:14,810
house.

2691
03:33:14,810 --> 03:33:21,569
He must be a very odd man, very unfriendly
certainly, but we are so glad to have Catherine

2692
03:33:21,569 --> 03:33:22,569
with us again.

2693
03:33:22,569 --> 03:33:28,430
And it is a great comfort to find that she
is not a poor helpless creature, but can manage

2694
03:33:28,430 --> 03:33:32,130
very well for herself.'

2695
03:33:32,130 --> 03:33:34,660
Mrs Allen was shocked.

2696
03:33:34,660 --> 03:33:40,000
She filled every pause in the conversation
by saying, 'I really have no patience with

2697
03:33:40,000 --> 03:33:41,260
the General.'

2698
03:33:41,260 --> 03:33:44,340
But she did not allow for many pauses.

2699
03:33:44,340 --> 03:33:49,029
'Bath is a nice place, Catherine, after all,'
she said brightly.

2700
03:33:49,029 --> 03:33:51,410
'I did not like the idea of leaving.

2701
03:33:51,410 --> 03:33:53,739
Did I tell you that I tore my blue dress?

2702
03:33:53,739 --> 03:33:57,910
I had it mended before we left Bath and you
cannot see the tear.

2703
03:33:57,910 --> 03:34:01,760
And Mrs Thorpe was such a comfort to us, wasn't
she?

2704
03:34:01,760 --> 03:34:04,410
You know, you and I were quite lonely at first.'

2705
03:34:04,410 --> 03:34:11,220
'Yes, but that did not last long,' Catherine
replied brightly, enjoying thoughts of Bath

2706
03:34:11,220 --> 03:34:12,630
and happier days.

2707
03:34:12,630 --> 03:34:13,830
'Very true.

2708
03:34:13,830 --> 03:34:16,739
Then we met Mrs Thorpe and were always busy.

2709
03:34:16,739 --> 03:34:21,000
My dear, do you think these silk gloves still
look well?

2710
03:34:21,000 --> 03:34:23,340
I wore them for the first time in Bath.

2711
03:34:23,340 --> 03:34:25,080
Do you remember that evening?'

2712
03:34:25,080 --> 03:34:28,850
'Oh, yes, perfectly,' answered Catherine.

2713
03:34:28,850 --> 03:34:32,270
'It was very agreeable, wasn't it?

2714
03:34:32,270 --> 03:34:36,750
Mr Tilney drank tea with us that evening,
and I thought he was an excellent addition

2715
03:34:36,750 --> 03:34:38,000
to our little society.

2716
03:34:38,000 --> 03:34:40,520
He is a kind gentleman, isn't he?

2717
03:34:40,520 --> 03:34:43,090
I think you probably danced with him that
evening.

2718
03:34:43,090 --> 03:34:47,859
I am not certain, but I was wearing my most
expensive dress, do you remember?

2719
03:34:47,859 --> 03:34:51,110
And Mr Tilney admired it very much.'

2720
03:34:51,110 --> 03:34:57,859
Catherine felt too emotional to answer, but
Mrs Allen continued, 'I really have no patience

2721
03:34:57,859 --> 03:34:58,990
with the General.

2722
03:34:58,990 --> 03:35:03,199
He seemed such an admirable gentleman when
we met him.

2723
03:35:03,199 --> 03:35:07,430
Do you know, Catherine, that his lodgings
were rented by another family the day after

2724
03:35:07,430 --> 03:35:09,160
he and his children left?

2725
03:35:09,160 --> 03:35:13,200
But no wonder - it was such a desirable address.'

2726
03:35:13,200 --> 03:35:22,590
As they walked home again, Mrs Morland said,
'You must be grateful for your old friends.

2727
03:35:22,590 --> 03:35:26,850
They have loved you and been concerned for
your happiness for many years.

2728
03:35:26,850 --> 03:35:35,220
Having the affection and good opinion of friends
like Mr and Mrs Allen is much more important

2729
03:35:35,220 --> 03:35:39,830
than your recent unhappy experience.'

2730
03:35:39,830 --> 03:35:44,551
Catherine knew that these were wise words,
but at that moment they meant little to her.

2731
03:35:44,551 --> 03:35:51,140
Her present happiness did not depend on old
friends, but on the behaviour of her newest

2732
03:35:51,140 --> 03:35:52,140
friends.

2733
03:35:52,140 --> 03:35:57,370
Mrs Morland continued encouraging her daughter
to forget about the people she had met at

2734
03:35:57,370 --> 03:36:01,609
Bath as they walked towards home.

2735
03:36:01,609 --> 03:36:06,239
Catherine listened politely to her mother,
but she was silently reflecting that now Henry

2736
03:36:06,239 --> 03:36:14,000
must have arrived at Northanger; now he must
have heard about her departure; and now, perhaps,

2737
03:36:14,000 --> 03:36:18,970
the family were leaving the Abbey for Hereford.

2738
03:36:18,970 --> 03:36:27,320
The following day, Mrs Morland sat with Catherine
and Sarah, her two eldest daughters, as they

2739
03:36:27,320 --> 03:36:29,380
worked at their various jobs.

2740
03:36:29,380 --> 03:36:35,120
Catherine had never been hard-working, nor
had she liked sitting indoors for very long,

2741
03:36:35,120 --> 03:36:39,590
but Mrs Morland noticed that her bad habits
had become even worse.

2742
03:36:39,590 --> 03:36:44,010
The seventeen-year-old could not sit still,
nor concentrate on a piece of work for even

2743
03:36:44,010 --> 03:36:45,830
ten minutes at a time.

2744
03:36:45,830 --> 03:36:51,500
She regularly stood up and walked around the
room or wandered into the garden.

2745
03:36:51,500 --> 03:36:53,330
Sitting quietly seemed impossible.

2746
03:36:53,330 --> 03:36:58,930
But worst of all to her mother was Catherine's
lack of energy and spirit.

2747
03:36:58,930 --> 03:37:05,160
She knew her daughter had never been a good
worker, but silence and sadness were unusual

2748
03:37:05,160 --> 03:37:06,160
for her.

2749
03:37:06,160 --> 03:37:10,560
What had happened to her old, cheerful personality?

2750
03:37:10,560 --> 03:37:17,739
For two days Mrs Morland allowed this behaviour
to pass without a hint of criticism, but when

2751
03:37:17,739 --> 03:37:23,260
a third night's rest still had not returned
Catherine to her old self, she decided to

2752
03:37:23,260 --> 03:37:26,220
have a serious talk with her daughter.

2753
03:37:26,220 --> 03:37:35,649
'My dear Catherine, I am afraid you have become
too grand for your own family.

2754
03:37:35,649 --> 03:37:38,529
Should your father mend his own shirts?

2755
03:37:38,529 --> 03:37:44,910
Look how steadily your sister is working,
while your head is still in Bath.

2756
03:37:44,910 --> 03:37:48,900
You must remember that there is a time for
everything.

2757
03:37:48,900 --> 03:37:56,439
Now is not the time for balls and theatre;
now is the time for you to be useful to me

2758
03:37:56,439 --> 03:38:00,310
and to your family.'

2759
03:38:00,310 --> 03:38:07,069
Catherine picked up her sewing basket and
sadly replied, 'I do not think about Bath.

2760
03:38:07,069 --> 03:38:10,850
At least, not very much.'

2761
03:38:10,850 --> 03:38:16,699
'Then you must still be upset about General
Tilney, and that is very silly of you.

2762
03:38:16,699 --> 03:38:20,029
You probably will never see him again.

2763
03:38:20,029 --> 03:38:25,680
You should not worry about things you cannot
change.'

2764
03:38:25,680 --> 03:38:30,970
After a short silence, she continued, 'I hope
you have not found your home disappointing

2765
03:38:30,970 --> 03:38:34,820
because it is not as elegant as Northanger
Abbey.

2766
03:38:34,820 --> 03:38:38,060
That would be turning your visit into something
evil.

2767
03:38:38,060 --> 03:38:44,149
Wherever you are, but especially in your own
home, you should learn to be content.

2768
03:38:44,149 --> 03:38:52,279
I was not happy to hear you at breakfast talking
so much about the French bread and the beautiful

2769
03:38:52,279 --> 03:38:54,609
plates at Northanger.'

2770
03:38:54,609 --> 03:39:00,670
'I am sure I do not care about any of that,'
said Catherine quietly.

2771
03:39:00,670 --> 03:39:07,620
'I have a book,' Mrs Morland said, 'with a
very clever essay about young ladies who have

2772
03:39:07,620 --> 03:39:12,310
been spoiled by making friends with people
who are much grander than their own families.

2773
03:39:12,310 --> 03:39:14,560
I will find it for you later.

2774
03:39:14,560 --> 03:39:19,070
I am sure it will do you good.'

2775
03:39:19,070 --> 03:39:24,109
Catherine tried to get on with her work, but
after a few minutes Mrs Morland saw her staring

2776
03:39:24,109 --> 03:39:26,489
out of the window again.

2777
03:39:26,489 --> 03:39:30,910
She came to the conclusion that her daughter
was suffering, and she hastily left the room

2778
03:39:30,910 --> 03:39:37,319
to find her book of clever essays.

2779
03:39:37,319 --> 03:39:38,319
CHAPTER TWELVE

2780
03:39:38,319 --> 03:39:40,900
Happily Ever After...

2781
03:39:40,900 --> 03:39:41,900
Eventually

2782
03:39:41,900 --> 03:39:49,779
It took at least fifteen minutes for Mrs Morland
to find her book of essays, and then she had

2783
03:39:49,779 --> 03:39:54,899
a few other tasks to complete before she could
return to her daughter.

2784
03:39:54,899 --> 03:40:01,189
And when she was able to return, she was surprised
to find a visitor there, someone whom she

2785
03:40:01,189 --> 03:40:02,989
had never seen before.

2786
03:40:02,989 --> 03:40:09,060
With a look of much respect, the young man
immediately rose, and Catherine introduced

2787
03:40:09,060 --> 03:40:11,489
Mr Henry Tilney to her mother.

2788
03:40:11,489 --> 03:40:15,890
Mr Tilney quickly began to apologise to Mrs
Morland.

2789
03:40:15,890 --> 03:40:19,290
'I am sorry to arrive here without an invitation.

2790
03:40:19,290 --> 03:40:25,210
I know that you cannot welcome a visitor from
Northanger Abbey after what happened to Miss

2791
03:40:25,210 --> 03:40:30,149
Morland there, but I was impatient to know
that she had arrived home safely.'

2792
03:40:30,149 --> 03:40:37,040
Mrs Morland had never blamed Henry or his
sister for their father's rude behaviour,

2793
03:40:37,040 --> 03:40:42,100
and now she was very pleased by this young
man's appearance and by his sincere apology.

2794
03:40:42,100 --> 03:40:47,120
'Thank you, Mr Tilney, for your kind treatment
of Catherine.

2795
03:40:47,120 --> 03:40:50,630
I believe you have nothing to apologise for.

2796
03:40:50,630 --> 03:40:57,310
You, and any friends of our children, are
always welcome to visit us at Fullerton.'

2797
03:40:57,310 --> 03:41:03,240
Then she continued with a list of polite questions
about Mr Tilney's journey, the weather and

2798
03:41:03,240 --> 03:41:05,960
the condition of the roads.

2799
03:41:05,960 --> 03:41:11,540
Meanwhile Catherine remained silent, but her
mother could see from her bright eyes and

2800
03:41:11,540 --> 03:41:19,020
rosy cheeks that she was very pleased by Mr
Tilney's presence, and Mrs Morland slipped

2801
03:41:19,020 --> 03:41:23,740
the book of essays into a convenient drawer
for a future hour.

2802
03:41:23,740 --> 03:41:30,520
Eventually Mrs Morland exhausted her supply
of polite questions, and Henry turned to Catherine

2803
03:41:30,520 --> 03:41:38,410
for the first time since her mother's entrance
and asked, 'Are Mr and Mrs Allen now at Fullerton?'

2804
03:41:38,410 --> 03:41:43,780
Catherine struggled to calm her nerves and
answer sensibly, but finally made it clear

2805
03:41:43,780 --> 03:41:45,840
that the Allens were at home.

2806
03:41:45,840 --> 03:41:51,319
'I would like to pay my respects to them,'
Mr Tilney said.

2807
03:41:51,319 --> 03:41:55,010
His face was now almost as red as Catherine's.

2808
03:41:55,010 --> 03:42:00,830
'I wonder if you would be kind enough to show
me the way to their house, Miss Morland?'

2809
03:42:00,830 --> 03:42:07,290
'You can see it from that window,' interrupted
Sarah, who continued to sew quietly but was

2810
03:42:07,290 --> 03:42:09,529
keeping an eye on what was happening.

2811
03:42:09,529 --> 03:42:16,350
Mr Tilney bowed politely, but Mrs Morland
gave her younger daughter a silencing nod.

2812
03:42:16,350 --> 03:42:22,460
They both understood that seeing the Allens
was not the primary purpose of Mr Tilney's

2813
03:42:22,460 --> 03:42:23,680
invitation.

2814
03:42:23,680 --> 03:42:28,020
Mrs Morland thought that he might want to
explain his father's behaviour to Catherine

2815
03:42:28,020 --> 03:42:34,810
in private, and she did not intend to put
any barriers in the way of that conversation;

2816
03:42:34,810 --> 03:42:39,819
she encouraged Catherine to walk to the Allens'
house with Mr Tilney.

2817
03:42:39,819 --> 03:42:48,970
Mrs Morland was correct: Henry Tilney did
want to explain his father's rudeness - a

2818
03:42:48,970 --> 03:42:54,220
difficult task for a son - but that was not
his primary reason for wanting to talk to

2819
03:42:54,220 --> 03:42:55,300
Catherine.

2820
03:42:55,300 --> 03:43:02,949
Above all, he wanted to explain himself, and
before they reached the Allens' house he had

2821
03:43:02,949 --> 03:43:05,310
done that extremely well.

2822
03:43:05,310 --> 03:43:11,449
In fact it was a speech that Catherine thought
could not be repeated too often.

2823
03:43:11,449 --> 03:43:20,510
Henry assured her of his affection, and asked
if he could hope that she also loved him - something

2824
03:43:20,510 --> 03:43:25,300
that you will have no doubts about by this
time.

2825
03:43:25,300 --> 03:43:31,920
Henry was sincerely and completely attached
to our heroine; he was delighted by her character

2826
03:43:31,920 --> 03:43:35,600
and truly loved spending all his time with
her.

2827
03:43:35,600 --> 03:43:41,850
But you must understand that his love and
affection for Catherine had its origin in

2828
03:43:41,850 --> 03:43:48,239
something quite simple; he had recognised
that she seemed to admire everything about

2829
03:43:48,239 --> 03:43:53,510
him, and for this he was very grateful.

2830
03:43:53,510 --> 03:43:59,320
So on this basis, although Henry would not
have been able to explain his reasons to himself,

2831
03:43:59,320 --> 03:44:04,390
he proposed marriage to Miss Catherine Morland.

2832
03:44:04,390 --> 03:44:10,330
The visit to Mr and Mrs Allen's house was
very short.

2833
03:44:10,330 --> 03:44:14,930
Both Catherine and Henry were thinking of
something much more important than chatting

2834
03:44:14,930 --> 03:44:16,229
about Bath.

2835
03:44:16,229 --> 03:44:22,380
Henry was polite, Catherine scarcely said
a word, and soon the young couple were happily

2836
03:44:22,380 --> 03:44:28,290
walking along the path together again, with
nothing to do except think of their future

2837
03:44:28,290 --> 03:44:29,800
life together.

2838
03:44:29,800 --> 03:44:36,670
Can you imagine the joy that filled our heroine's
heart?

2839
03:44:36,670 --> 03:44:42,030
She floated along beside Mr Tilney in a cloud
of happiness, as he talked about this and

2840
03:44:42,030 --> 03:44:43,030
that.

2841
03:44:43,030 --> 03:44:48,600
But she listened carefully when her dear Henry
said that he did not have his father's permission

2842
03:44:48,600 --> 03:44:49,609
to approach her.

2843
03:44:49,609 --> 03:44:56,859
On his return from Woodston, two days earlier,
he had been met near the Abbey by his impatient

2844
03:44:56,859 --> 03:44:57,859
father.

2845
03:44:57,859 --> 03:45:03,290
In very angry terms the General had insisted
that Henry should never think of Miss Catherine

2846
03:45:03,290 --> 03:45:04,860
Morland again.

2847
03:45:04,860 --> 03:45:10,790
This information shocked Catherine, but more
important was the fact that Henry wanted to

2848
03:45:10,790 --> 03:45:11,870
marry her.

2849
03:45:11,870 --> 03:45:17,760
Knowing that she was loved gave her the courage
to try to understand the motives for General

2850
03:45:17,760 --> 03:45:21,899
Tilney's actions and for his disapproval of
her.

2851
03:45:21,899 --> 03:45:27,939
As Henry's story unfolded, her curiosity turned
to delight.

2852
03:45:27,939 --> 03:45:34,040
His father had found no reason to criticise
Catherine's behaviour or her character; he

2853
03:45:34,040 --> 03:45:40,189
was, instead, disappointed by his own actions
and ashamed of having been misled by Mr John

2854
03:45:40,189 --> 03:45:41,189
Thorpe.

2855
03:45:41,189 --> 03:45:47,060
Catherine, it seemed, was guilty of only one
thing in the General's opinion: she was less

2856
03:45:47,060 --> 03:45:49,670
rich than he had supposed her to be.

2857
03:45:49,670 --> 03:45:55,770
The General had been deceived by John Thorpe
at their first meeting, at the theatre in

2858
03:45:55,770 --> 03:45:56,949
Bath.

2859
03:45:56,949 --> 03:46:02,090
On that occasion, Henry had been talking to
Catherine and the General had asked Mr Thorpe

2860
03:46:02,090 --> 03:46:04,149
if he knew the young lady.

2861
03:46:04,149 --> 03:46:11,729
John Thorpe had a misleading, and even dangerous,
habit of exaggerating the importance and wealth

2862
03:46:11,729 --> 03:46:16,830
of his friends and acquaintances; he seemed
to think that this made him more important

2863
03:46:16,830 --> 03:46:18,250
in the eyes of the world.

2864
03:46:18,250 --> 03:46:24,760
When he had become friends with James Morland,
he had reported to his family that he had

2865
03:46:24,760 --> 03:46:32,090
met a young man from a very grand family;
then, introducing James to Isabella, he had

2866
03:46:32,090 --> 03:46:36,729
doubled the amount of his friend's living,
multiplied his private fortune by three or

2867
03:46:36,729 --> 03:46:42,569
four times, invented a rich aunt for him,
and forgot about half of James's brothers

2868
03:46:42,569 --> 03:46:43,569
and sisters.

2869
03:46:43,569 --> 03:46:49,500
John Thorpe had continued with this practice
of exaggeration when telling General Tilney

2870
03:46:49,500 --> 03:46:50,790
about the Morland family.

2871
03:46:50,790 --> 03:46:57,010
He had invented a large private income for
Catherine, whom he himself had decided to

2872
03:46:57,010 --> 03:47:02,860
marry, as well as the promise that she would
one day receive an enormous inheritance from

2873
03:47:02,860 --> 03:47:04,430
the Allens.

2874
03:47:04,430 --> 03:47:10,210
With this information, which he had no reason
to doubt, General Tilney had decided to welcome

2875
03:47:10,210 --> 03:47:15,470
Miss Morland to Northanger Abbey and to encourage
his son to consider Miss Catherine Morland

2876
03:47:15,470 --> 03:47:18,069
as a possible bride.

2877
03:47:18,069 --> 03:47:22,310
Henry and Eleanor knew nothing about their
father's conversation with John Thorpe; they

2878
03:47:22,310 --> 03:47:27,450
were astonished by the kind, friendly attention
he showed towards Catherine, and the clear

2879
03:47:27,450 --> 03:47:31,940
signals he gave Henry that he approved of
her as his son's future wife.

2880
03:47:31,940 --> 03:47:37,159
But on his visit to London, the General had
met Mr John Thorpe again.

2881
03:47:37,159 --> 03:47:42,170
The younger man was by that time suffering
from what he considered to be ill treatment

2882
03:47:42,170 --> 03:47:49,080
by both James and Catherine Morland: she had
refused his proposal of marriage and James

2883
03:47:49,080 --> 03:47:51,730
would not accept Isabella's apologies.

2884
03:47:51,730 --> 03:47:57,069
Now he was eager to change the General's good
opinion of the whole Morland family.

2885
03:47:57,069 --> 03:48:02,600
This time he gave a more accurate account
of how many Morland children there were and

2886
03:48:02,600 --> 03:48:09,279
the amount of money and possessions the parents
had; in fact, he mentioned too many of one

2887
03:48:09,279 --> 03:48:11,310
and too few of the other.

2888
03:48:11,310 --> 03:48:13,620
And the Allens?

2889
03:48:13,620 --> 03:48:20,600
Their entire fortune would be inherited by
one of Mr Allen's nephews.

2890
03:48:20,600 --> 03:48:26,800
Angry with almost everyone in the world except
himself, the General had returned to the Abbey,

2891
03:48:26,800 --> 03:48:31,100
where you have seen how he behaved towards
our heroine.

2892
03:48:31,100 --> 03:48:38,270
Having heard all this, Catherine forgave herself
for thinking that General Tilney could either

2893
03:48:38,270 --> 03:48:40,729
have murdered or imprisoned his wife.

2894
03:48:40,729 --> 03:48:46,300
Now she understood how cruel he could be in
reality.

2895
03:48:46,300 --> 03:48:51,949
Poor Henry was blushing with shame while telling
Catherine this story.

2896
03:48:51,949 --> 03:48:57,189
He had had an angry conversation with his
father at Northanger Abbey, and had shocked

2897
03:48:57,189 --> 03:49:01,290
the General by refusing to agree with his
judgement of Catherine.

2898
03:49:01,290 --> 03:49:07,620
He felt tied to Catherine as much by honour
as affection; he would not dismiss her from

2899
03:49:07,620 --> 03:49:09,880
his heart or from his life.

2900
03:49:09,880 --> 03:49:15,859
He refused to accompany Eleanor and his father
to Herefordshire, and declared his intention

2901
03:49:15,859 --> 03:49:17,671
of asking Miss Morland to marry him.

2902
03:49:17,671 --> 03:49:26,529
General Tilney had been angrier than he had
ever been with his son, and the two had parted

2903
03:49:26,529 --> 03:49:28,880
without speaking to each other again.

2904
03:49:28,880 --> 03:49:35,390
Henry had returned to Woodston, and had begun
his journey to Fullerton on the following

2905
03:49:35,390 --> 03:49:37,399
afternoon.

2906
03:49:37,399 --> 03:49:46,390
Mr and Mrs Morland were quite astonished to
be asked by Mr Henry Tilney for permission

2907
03:49:46,390 --> 03:49:48,130
to marry their daughter.

2908
03:49:48,130 --> 03:49:54,189
They had not suspected a connection between
the two young people, but they believed Catherine

2909
03:49:54,189 --> 03:49:58,680
was worth loving and they soon happily accepted
the situation.

2910
03:49:58,680 --> 03:50:04,790
They had no reason to object to the marriage,
not having heard anything negative about Henry

2911
03:50:04,790 --> 03:50:07,729
and liking his pleasing manners and good sense.

2912
03:50:07,729 --> 03:50:15,620
Mrs Morland's only additional comment was,
'I am sure Catherine will make a poor housekeeper,

2913
03:50:15,620 --> 03:50:18,960
but practice is a good teacher.'

2914
03:50:18,960 --> 03:50:25,859
Nevertheless, even with everyone celebrating
the proposal, Mr and Mrs Morland could not

2915
03:50:25,859 --> 03:50:27,760
approve of the engagement.

2916
03:50:27,760 --> 03:50:35,270
They had mild tempers, but their principles
were strong; they did not expect heartfelt

2917
03:50:35,270 --> 03:50:39,069
approval from the General, but they required
his agreement, at least.

2918
03:50:39,069 --> 03:50:46,250
They assured the pair that they would be happy
for them to marry when that agreement was

2919
03:50:46,250 --> 03:50:52,351
obtained, but not before, and they trusted
that it would not be denied for long.

2920
03:50:52,351 --> 03:50:58,960
There need be no expectation of money from
the father, since his son's present income

2921
03:50:58,960 --> 03:51:06,359
already made him independent and comfortable,
their daughter could not hope for more.

2922
03:51:06,359 --> 03:51:08,170
The young people were not surprised by this
decision.

2923
03:51:08,170 --> 03:51:13,420
They were, of course, upset, but they parted
from each other with the hope that the General's

2924
03:51:13,420 --> 03:51:16,170
opinion could be changed very soon.

2925
03:51:16,170 --> 03:51:22,409
Henry returned to what was now his only home,
at Woodston, to look after his parish and

2926
03:51:22,409 --> 03:51:28,159
to make improvements to his house for his
future wife; Catherine remained at Fullerton

2927
03:51:28,159 --> 03:51:32,899
to cry rather dramatically and to look forward
to regular letters from Henry.

2928
03:51:32,899 --> 03:51:38,130
We need not enquire whether the difficulties
of absence were made easier by such secret

2929
03:51:38,130 --> 03:51:39,130
communication.

2930
03:51:39,130 --> 03:51:45,500
Mr and Mrs Morland never did - they had been
too kind to demand promises and whenever Catherine

2931
03:51:45,500 --> 03:51:50,630
received a letter, which happened quite often,
they always looked the other way.

2932
03:51:50,630 --> 03:51:57,310
As we approach the last of these pages, you
will have guessed that a happy ending is promised

2933
03:51:57,310 --> 03:51:58,470
very soon.

2934
03:51:58,470 --> 03:52:02,930
The only doubt can be the way in which perfect
happiness was achieved.

2935
03:52:02,930 --> 03:52:07,939
What circumstance could possibly change the
General's opinion of a marriage between his

2936
03:52:07,939 --> 03:52:09,649
son and Miss Morland?

2937
03:52:09,649 --> 03:52:11,960
The answer was another marriage.

2938
03:52:11,960 --> 03:52:18,109
In the course of the summer, Eleanor Tilney
married a young man with a large fortune and

2939
03:52:18,109 --> 03:52:20,409
a very respectable position in society.

2940
03:52:20,409 --> 03:52:27,290
Such an addition to his own importance threw
the General into a good mood for months, and

2941
03:52:27,290 --> 03:52:31,810
Eleanor insisted that he must forgive Henry
and accept Catherine as his future daughter-in-law.

2942
03:52:31,810 --> 03:52:39,740
Everyone who knows Eleanor Tilney will, I
am sure, congratulate her and wish her well

2943
03:52:39,740 --> 03:52:45,310
in the home and with the man of her choice,
away from the strict discipline of Northanger

2944
03:52:45,310 --> 03:52:46,310
Abbey.

2945
03:52:46,310 --> 03:52:49,960
My own joy on the occasion is very sincere.

2946
03:52:49,960 --> 03:52:56,090
I know of no one who, after all her suffering,
deserves happiness more.

2947
03:52:56,090 --> 03:53:02,290
And her husband was a young man who truly
deserved her: he was not only rich and important,

2948
03:53:02,290 --> 03:53:04,640
but also affectionate and charming.

2949
03:53:04,640 --> 03:53:10,000
Eleanor had known him for years, but General
Tilney had approved of him as little as he

2950
03:53:10,000 --> 03:53:15,729
approved of Catherine, and for the same reason:
he came from a respectable family with no

2951
03:53:15,729 --> 03:53:16,729
money.

2952
03:53:16,729 --> 03:53:24,260
But then this young man inherited an enormous
fortune as well as a title, and the General's

2953
03:53:24,260 --> 03:53:26,110
opinion changed immediately.

2954
03:53:26,110 --> 03:53:31,441
Suddenly he too could see that Eleanor's future
husband was the most charming young man in

2955
03:53:31,441 --> 03:53:32,441
the world.

2956
03:53:32,441 --> 03:53:38,790
And I should add that this was the same gentleman
whose careless servant left the laundry lists

2957
03:53:38,790 --> 03:53:46,310
in a drawer at Northanger Abbey and involved
our heroine in one of her most alarming adventures.

2958
03:53:46,310 --> 03:53:53,189
Eleanor and her delightful, rich husband used
their influence to persuade the General that

2959
03:53:53,189 --> 03:53:56,810
Henry should be allowed to marry Catherine
Morland.

2960
03:53:56,810 --> 03:54:02,649
In fact, they explained that Catherine was
not, in fact, poor and would have an income

2961
03:54:02,649 --> 03:54:08,340
of her own of three thousand pounds a year,
and that her father was much wealthier than

2962
03:54:08,340 --> 03:54:12,630
John Thorpe had reported during his second
meeting with General Tilney.

2963
03:54:12,630 --> 03:54:19,199
As a result of this happy news, the General
soon permitted his son to return to Northanger

2964
03:54:19,199 --> 03:54:24,550
Abbey and wrote to Mr Morland, politely giving
his agreement to the marriage of his younger

2965
03:54:24,550 --> 03:54:27,560
son and the Morlands' eldest daughter.

2966
03:54:27,560 --> 03:54:34,739
The event which the General's letter permitted
soon followed: Henry and Catherine were married,

2967
03:54:34,739 --> 03:54:38,180
the church bells rang and everybody celebrated.

2968
03:54:38,180 --> 03:54:44,680
The wedding took place less than twelve months
after the young couple had met, so the General's

2969
03:54:44,680 --> 03:54:48,210
cruelty did not hurt them very much or for
very long.

2970
03:54:48,210 --> 03:54:54,010
To begin perfect happiness at twenty-six and
eighteen is to do quite well.

2971
03:54:54,010 --> 03:54:59,970
I should add, moreover, that perhaps the General
added to this happiness by delaying the marriage

2972
03:54:59,970 --> 03:55:07,390
and giving them time to improve their knowledge
of each other and to strengthen their attachment.

2973
03:55:07,390 --> 03:55:13,319
I leave it for you to make a final judgement
on this question: Is the purpose of this story

2974
03:55:13,319 --> 03:55:18,649
to recommend parental cruelty, or to reward
a son's disobedience?

